   =20
      FTX
   =20
 =20

Of course there will be several FTX movies, and maybe the most cinematic sc=
ene in the whole story is the meeting that Caroline Ellison, the chief exec=
utive officer of Alameda Research, FTX=E2=80=99s affiliated trading firm, h=
eld to tell her employees that they=E2=80=99d been stealing FTX customer mo=
ney. Imagine! Imagine coming into the company all-hands meeting at the lucr=
ative trading firm you work at, in the Bahamas, far away from your friends =
and family and competitors, in a slightly cult-like environment where your =
 every need is catered to out of the firm=E2=80=99s enormous profits. And t=
hen your 28-year-old boss is like =E2=80=9Cso guys, a little bad news, actu=
ally we=E2=80=99re a Ponzi? Sorry if I didn=E2=80=99t mention that earlier.=
=E2=80=9D Everyone quit immediately, but much too late.=C2=A0
That meeting happened on Nov. 9, the day after FTX death-spiraled and tried=
 to sell itself to Binance, and has been reported before. But now Ellison i=
s cooperating with prosecutors and regulators, so we have their version of =
her version of the meeting and, oof. Here is how the US Commodity Futures T=
rading Commission describes it:
On the morning of November 9 at approximately 10 AM ET, after the announcem=
ent of the then-contemplated Binance acquisition, Ellison held an =E2=80=9C=
all-hands=E2=80=9D meeting with Alameda staff. In that meeting, Ellison ack=
nowledged that earlier that year, she, Bankman-Fried and other individuals =
had decided to use FTX customer assets to pay Alameda=E2=80=99s debts, and =
that Wang and another FTX executive were aware of this. Specifically, in th=
at meeting, Ellison stated that, =E2=80=9Cstarting last year=E2=80=9D Alame=
da was =E2=80=9Cborrowing a bunch of money by open term loans=E2=80=9D and =
used those assets to =E2=80=9Cmake very illiquid investments.=E2=80=9D Elli=
son further explained that following the widespread decline of digital asse=
t prices most of Alameda=E2=80=99s loans had been recalled and, in order to=
 meet those recalls, Alameda borrowed =E2=80=9Ca bunch of funds=E2=80=9D fr=
om FTX, which in turn =E2=80=9Cled to FTX having a shortfall in user funds.=
=E2=80=9D Ellison informed Alameda staff that FTX had =E2=80=9Calways allow=
ed=E2=80=9D Alameda to borrow customer assets, and did not require collater=
al for those loans. She=C2=A0also explained that Alameda could access user =
assets without requiring FTX=E2=80=99s approval as the =E2=80=9Cstructure=
=E2=80=9D allowed Alameda to =E2=80=9Cgo negative in coins.=E2=80=9D In res=
ponse to an employee question, Ellison also acknowledged that her November =
6 tweet to the Binance CEO offering to buy his FTT holdings at $22 per toke=
n was =E2=80=9Ckind of a misleading thing to tweet=E2=80=9D and expressed r=
emorse. Shortly after this meeting, most of Alameda=E2=80=99s staff resigne=
d.
=E2=80=9CGo negative in coins=E2=80=9D is an incredible euphemism, really. =
The idea is that Alameda could deposit, say, 1,000 Bitcoin at FTX, and then=
 it would have a balance of 1,000 Bitcoin. And then it could withdraw, say,=
 3,000 Bitcoin from FTX, and then it would have a balance of -2,000 Bitcoin=
. If you have a negative balance at your bank, bad things happen. When Alam=
eda had a negative balance at FTX, that was just fine. Until it wasn=E2=80=
=99t.
Ellison and Gary Wang, the former chief technology officer of FTX, have agr=
eed to plead guilty to federal fraud charges for their role in the FTX impl=
osion. (The plea agreements say that  Ellison and  Wang=C2=A0face maximum s=
entences of 110 and 50 years in prison, respectively, though presumably the=
y will end up with=C2=A0substantial discounts for cooperating.) Last night,=
 Sam Bankman-Fried, the founder of FTX and Alameda,  landed in New York to =
face similar charges. There is something of a prisoner=E2=80=99s-dilemma si=
tuation here, in that there was=C2=A0in theory=C2=A0the possibility that=C2=
=A0everyone at FTX=C2=A0and Alameda could have stuck together and said=C2=
=A0=E2=80=9Cwhat, we never did anything wrong,=E2=80=9D and that they might=
 have=C2=A0persuaded a jury of that. The odds were always low, but it is th=
e approach that Bankman-Fried has taken in public interviews. Bloomberg=E2=
=80=99s  Zeke Faux reported=C2=A0earlier this month:

Part of FTX=E2=80=99s appeal was that it was mostly a derivatives exchange,=
 which allowed customers to trade =E2=80=9Con margin,=E2=80=9D meaning with=
 borrowed money. That=E2=80=99s a key to his defense. Bankman-Fried argues =
no one should be surprised that big traders on FTX, including Alameda, were=
 borrowing from the exchange, and that his fund=E2=80=99s position just som=
ehow got out of hand. =E2=80=9CEveryone was borrowing and lending,=E2=80=9D=
 he says. =E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=99s been its calling card.=E2=80=9D But FTX=
=E2=80=99s normal margin system, crypto traders tell me, would never have p=
ermitted anyone to accumulate a debt that looked like Alameda=E2=80=99s. Wh=
en I ask if Alameda had to follow the same margin rules as other traders, h=
e admits the fund did not. =E2=80=9CThere was more leeway,=E2=80=9D he says=
. =E2=80=A6
Ellison said that she, Bankman-Fried and his two top lieutenants=E2=80=94Ga=
ry Wang and Nishad Singh=E2=80=94had discussed the shortfall. Instead of ad=
mitting Alameda=E2=80=99s failure, they decided to use FTX customer funds t=
o cover it, according to the people. If that=E2=80=99s true, all four execu=
tives would=E2=80=99ve knowingly committed fraud. =E2=80=A6
=E2=80=9CSo, it=E2=80=99s not how I remember what happened,=E2=80=9D Bankma=
n-Fried says. But he surprises me by acknowledging that there had been a me=
eting, post-Luna crash, where they debated what to do about Alameda=E2=80=
=99s debts. The way he tells it, he was packing for a trip to DC and =E2=80=
=9Conly kibitzing on parts of the discussion.=E2=80=9D It didn=E2=80=99t se=
em like a crisis, he says. It was a matter of extending a bit more credit t=
o a fund that already traded on margin and still had a pile of collateral w=
orth way more than enough to cover the loan.

This is=C2=A0a story in which FTX was operating its legitimate business =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0extending margin leverage to traders on its exchange =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0and made some mistakes. The mistakes were very bad =E2=80=94=C2=A0the=
y involved giving billions of dollars to Alameda, which it could not pay ba=
ck, blowing up FTX and taking customer money with it =E2=80=94=C2=A0and als=
o=C2=A0very suspicious, in that FTX gave this generous credit only to its o=
wn affiliated=C2=A0trading firm,=C2=A0secured largely by tokens that FTX ha=
d invented, and Alameda was lending a lot of that money to FTX/Alameda=E2=
=80=99s principals for their own personal purposes. And,   as I have   argu=
ed, even if this story was true, it is not much of a defense to fraud charg=
es, because FTX was going around telling everyone that it had good automate=
d risk systems that would prevent it from doing exactly this sort of dumb t=
hing, and lying about that   is itself fraud. Again, I don=E2=80=99t think =
this would have worked. But I suppose if you got a bunch of smart earnest 2=
0-somethings up on the witness stand and they all said =E2=80=9Cyes we were=
 extending credit to a margin customer, ordinary-course stuff, but then the=
 market blew up and the loans defaulted,=E2=80=9D there was a=C2=A0chance.=
=C2=A0
But now Ellison and Wang will get up on the witness stand and, I assume, sa=
y something like =E2=80=9Coh obviously we knew that was fraud, we were just=
 doing it to steal customer money, we talked about that all the time.=E2=80=
=9D It=E2=80=99s hard to see how Bankman-Fried could rebut that. Just on pa=
per the facts are very bad, but when you add the testimony of his friends t=
hey become impossible.
The other new news from Ellison and Wang=E2=80=99s cooperation is about the=
 alleged manipulation of FTT tokens.
  [1]
=C2=A0The US Securities and Exchange Commission explains:
Beyond its =E2=80=9Cline of credit=E2=80=9D with FTX, Ellison, at Bankman-F=
ried=E2=80=99s direction, caused Alameda to borrow billions of dollars from=
 third party lenders. Those loans were backed in significant part by Alamed=
a=E2=80=99s holdings of FTT=E2=80=94an illiquid crypto asset security that =
was issued by FTX and provided to Alameda at no cost. Ellison, acting at th=
e direction of Bankman-Fried, engaged in automated purchases of FTT tokens =
on various platforms in order to increase the price of those tokens and inf=
late the value of Alameda=E2=80=99s collateral, which allowed Alameda to bo=
rrow even more money from external lenders at increased risk to the lenders=
 and to FTX=E2=80=99s investors and customers, all in furtherance of the sc=
heme.
And:

In July 2019, when FTX launched FTT, Alameda received a substantial portion=
 of the 350 million FTT tokens that were minted, including all of the =E2=
=80=9Ccompany tokens=E2=80=9D that were allocated to FTX. Alameda did not p=
ay for these tokens.
Alameda programmed its automated trading tools (or =E2=80=9Cbots=E2=80=9D) =
to conduct trades and execute transactions to purchase FTT at specific pric=
es. On more than one occasion, Alameda and Ellison, at Bankman-Fried=E2=80=
=99s direction, actively engaged in the trading of FTT with the goal of sup=
porting the price of the token. On these occasions, Alameda adjusted the tr=
ading parameters of its trading bots in order to support the price of FTT.
For example, in 2019, there was downward pressure on the price of FTT as th=
e token was being unlocked for early-stage investors. Bankman-Fried became =
concerned about, among other things, the psychological effect of the price =
of FTT dropping below a specific threshold, and instructed Ellison to have =
Alameda purchase FTT to support the price and avoid that outcome. In anothe=
r instance in 2021, the price of FTT was again facing downward pressure fro=
m external events, this time related to substantial sales of FTT by a third=
 party. Bankman-Fried again instructed Ellison to have Alameda purchase FTT=
 on trading platforms to support the price.

Here again you might be able to get around the objective facts, which are b=
asically that Alameda, a crypto market maker, was buying FTT tokens when ot=
her people were selling. But if the CEO of Alameda gets on the stand and sa=
ys =E2=80=9Cyes Sam Bankman-Fried told me to buy FTT tokens to manipulate t=
he price up so that we could continue to borrow billions of dollars against=
 the inflated token we invented,=E2=80=9D that is harder to explain away.
The question I always have in situations like this is: How did they=C2=A0th=
ink=C2=A0this would go? What was the=C2=A0good=C2=A0outcome here? Why do=C2=
=A0all this?=C2=A0Many financial crimes have essentially the shape of Ponzi=
 schemes, which by their nature snowball: You take some money from new cust=
omers to pay fake returns to old customers, which requires you to take even=
 more money from newer customers to keep paying the fake returns, etc., unt=
il the hole gets too big and you go to prison. If you start by stealing $1,=
000, pretty soon you need to steal $10,000, and then $100,000, and then you=
 find yourself running a billion-dollar Ponzi. And there=E2=80=99s rarely a=
 way to come back from that. It is hard to make back a billion dollars at t=
he roulette tables.
You can keep this=C2=A0going=C2=A0for a while, if you are good and lucky; B=
ernie Madoff ran a huge Ponzi for years. But that doesn=E2=80=99t really=C2=
=A0help. The longer you run the Ponzi, the deeper the hole gets; being resp=
ectable and trusted for decades doesn=E2=80=99t really get you the billions=
 of dollars you need to plug the hole. It is hard to grow your way out of i=
t; growth mostly makes the problem worse.
But there is something different about running a crypto exchange, taking ou=
t margin loans against tokens that you made up to invest in crypto venture =
capital projects. The asset that you are borrowing against is essentially=
=C2=A0confidence in you: in your exchange, in crypto generally, in your rol=
e as a leading figure in crypto. If that collapses, then your finances coll=
apse and you find yourself in a Bahamian jail cell. But what if it doesn't?=
 If you go on long enough, then those FTT tokens that you made up =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0that entitle customers to discounts on FTX trading fees and a share o=
f FTX revenue =E2=80=94=C2=A0become more and more valuable, and your decisi=
on to lend money against them looks fine. (Your decision to=C2=A0manipulate=
 them looks fine, too, because in hindsight you can say =E2=80=9Cof course =
we bought when people were selling, we thought they were a bargain, and we =
were right.=E2=80=9D) Ultimately maybe those tokens become so valuable that=
 they dwarf the customer money that you, uh, misplaced, and you can easily =
plug the hole with the=C2=A0tokens.
Earlier this year, we   talked a   lot about Terra, a crypto project that c=
ollapsed when its TerraUSD stablecoin spiraled to zero. The=C2=A0plan, with=
 Terra, was for it to become so popular and widely accepted that people wou=
ld pay a lot of money for Luna, its native token, and then Terra=E2=80=99s =
promoters would sell a bunch of Luna to raise money to make TerraUSD a full=
y backed stablecoin. =E2=80=9C=E2=80=9CThe basic structure of the trade,=E2=
=80=9D   I wrote,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cis (1) Ponzi, (2) acceptance, (3) diversifi=
cation, (4) permanence.=E2=80=9D This did not work, because before Terra co=
uld complete its diversification it lost market confidence, and everything =
went to zero.=C2=A0But I don=E2=80=99t think it was a terrible plan. If Ter=
ra had=C2=A0managed to be widely accepted for long enough, it could have=C2=
=A0printed its own money, and then=C2=A0exchanged that for real money, and =
then everything would have been great. So close!
FTX, too, printed its own money, and treated it as money. At the end, as FT=
X was spiraling into bankruptcy, as the Binance bailout was falling apart, =
as Caroline Ellison was telling employees about the missing customer money,=
 Sam Bankman-Fried was   pitching potential rescuers with a spreadsheet sho=
wing that FTX was still solvent. That spreadsheet relied on billions of dol=
lars of tokens =E2=80=94=C2=A0FTT but also weirder things like Serum and Ma=
ps =E2=80=94=C2=A0that FTX had made up, that it owned most of, and that had=
 no real independent market value. They were worth billions as long as ever=
yone believed in FTX, and nothing otherwise. By the time Bankman-Fried was =
circulating the spreadsheet, they were worth nothing. But he only needed to=
 find one person who believed.
I   keep quoting it because it is such cinematic foreshadowing, but last ye=
ar Bankman-Fried   said to me on a podcast:

You start with a company that builds a box and in practice this box, they p=
robably dress it up to look like a life-changing, you know, world-altering =
protocol that's gonna replace all the big banks in 38 days or whatever. May=
be for now actually ignore what it does or pretend it does literally nothin=
g. It's just a box. So what this protocol is, it's called =E2=80=98Protocol=
 X,=E2=80=99 it's a box, and you take a token. =E2=80=A6
So you've got this box=C2=A0and it=E2=80=99s kind of dumb, but like what's =
the end game, right? This box is worth zero obviously. =E2=80=A6 But on the=
 other hand, if everyone kind of now thinks that this box token is worth ab=
out a billion dollar market cap, that's what people are pricing it at and s=
ort of has that market cap.=C2=A0

He went on in a cynical vein:
In=C2=A0fact, you can even finance this, right? You put X token in a borrow=
 lending protocol and borrow dollars with it. If you think it's worth like =
less than two thirds of that, you could even just like put some in there, t=
ake the dollars out. Never, you know, give the dollars back. You just get l=
iquidated eventually.=C2=A0
And that is what happened: FTX got liquidated eventually, and now he=E2=80=
=99s facing fraud charges. But it was not obvious, in advance, that that wa=
s how it had to go. Maybe the box was life-changing, a world-altering proto=
col that was gonna replace all the big banks. Maybe you never get liquidate=
d; maybe=C2=A0 everyone will keep believing in the box until it becomes rea=
l.=C2=A0

