   =20
 =20

Honestly the APE thing is pretty clever. AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc. ha=
s one incredible advantage=C2=A0and one bizarre constraint. The advantage i=
s that AMC is really really good at raising equity: It rode last year=E2=80=
=99s meme-stock wave   more expertly than anyone else, using retail investo=
rs=E2=80=99 enthusiasm for its stock=C2=A0to sell lots of stock at attracti=
ve prices to pay down debt.=C2=A0
The constraint is that, like most public companies, AMC has a corporate cha=
rter that=C2=A0limits the number of shares it can issue, and it is   basica=
lly all out of shares. To get more shares, it needs to get a majority of it=
s shareholders to approve an amendment to the corporate charter authorizing=
 more shares, and this is hard, for two reasons:
=09Some shareholders seem to dislike the idea of being =E2=80=9Cdiluted=E2=
=80=9D if AMC issues more shares. This strikes me as misguided =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0if a company sells stock at a price that is too high, that=E2=80=99s acc=
retive! =E2=80=94=C2=A0but people worry.=09More important, AMC has tons of =
retail shareholders, and=C2=A0retail shareholders, stereotypically,   don=
=E2=80=99t vote. It needs a majority of all shares to vote in favor of the =
charter amendment, and it=E2=80=99s hard to do that if many of your shareho=
lders don=E2=80=99t vote at all.

And so AMC   came up with a novel idea. It couldn=E2=80=99t sell any more c=
ommon shares, so it would sell APE shares, =E2=80=9CAMC Preferred Equity un=
its,=E2=80=9D a weird new instrument designed to look like common stock.=C2=
=A0The APE shares=C2=A0are not common stock, so they are not covered by the=
 cap in=C2=A0the certificate of incorporation, but they are=C2=A0like=C2=A0=
common stock in most important ways. They are listed on the stock exchange =
and they have the same economic rights (to dividends, etc.) as the common s=
tock does. Also, crucially, they=C2=A0vote=C2=A0with the common stock: Anyt=
hing that needs shareholder approval is submitted to a combined vote of the=
 common and APE shares; each share, common or APE, gets one vote.=C2=A0
AMC did not start by selling APEs; it started by giving them away. It distr=
ibuted APEs to its existing common shareholders, one APE per common share; =
the result was basically like a stock split, where if you previously had 10=
0 shares now you had 200, except half of them were APEs. This created a mar=
ket for the APEs =E2=80=94=C2=A0now people had them, they were bought and s=
old=C2=A0on the stock exchange. And=C2=A0then=C2=A0AMC started  selling APE=
s to raise money. It was out of common shares, but it still had APEs.
In theory there were three ways this could go:
=09The APEs and common shares, being more or less identical, would trade at=
 more or less the same price. It would be like any other company with dual-=
class shares. AMC would keep issuing more APEs to raise financing, and woul=
d get about as much money for the APEs as it would for its common stock. No=
body would worry about the small differences between APEs and common shares=
.=09The APEs would be worth=C2=A0more=C2=A0than the common stock, because t=
hey are funny? The ticker is APE. They are preferred stock, which you might=
 think makes them preferable to the common stock. In this case, AMC would k=
eep issuing APEs to raise financing, and would get more money for the APEs =
than it would for common stock, and would have created some value out of no=
thing. Or, rather, would have created some value out of leaning into the me=
me-stock thing, which is how it creates value generally.=09The APEs would b=
e worth=C2=A0less=C2=A0than the common stock, because common stock is a nor=
mal obvious standard thing, while a weird preferred unit is weird. In this =
case, AMC would have no choice but to keep issuing APEs to raise financing =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0it can=E2=80=99t sell more common shares! =E2=80=94=C2=A0but=
 would get less for those APEs than it would for its common stock. The APE =
financings would be dilutive: AMC would sell APEs for less than the price o=
f common stock, but the APEs would have the same economic rights as common =
stock. This would be bad.

Option 3 was the most likely, and it is in fact what happened. When APEs st=
arted trading in August, they were worth about $6 or $7 per share, while th=
e common stock was around $9 or $10. Yesterday the common stock closed at $=
5.30; the APEs closed at $0.685, an 87% discount. That=E2=80=99s bad. If yo=
ur common stock is worth $5.30, selling basically-common-stock for $0.685 i=
s a bad corporate finance move.
But this problem comes with its own solution. AMC can still go back to shar=
eholders anytime and ask them to vote to collapse this back into a normal s=
ingle-share structure, by authorizing=C2=A0more common shares and convertin=
g the APE shares into common shares. If a majority of shareholders approve,=
 then each APE will turn into a common share, closing the discount. Maybe t=
he common shares will maintain their value and the APEs will go up to $5.30=
, or maybe they=E2=80=99ll both end up worth, say, $3, but in any case they=
=E2=80=99ll all be the same thing and trade at the same price.
And, when AMC puts that proposition to a vote, the common shareholders and =
the APE holders will all vote together. There will be=C2=A0more=C2=A0APE sh=
ares than common shares: Originally the APEs were distributed to common sha=
reholders 1 for 1, creating an equal number of APEs and common shares, and =
since then AMC has sold more APEs while the common share supply is capped. =
So the majority of voting shares belong to the APEs, which trade at a disco=
unt to the common. The APEs have every reason to vote to collapse their APE=
s back into common stock to close the discount. The bigger the discount is,=
 the more incentive they have to vote. And, the bigger the discount is, the=
 more likely it is that some professional=C2=A0investor =E2=80=94=C2=A0a he=
dge fund, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0will buy up the APEs=C2=A0in order to=C2=A0vo=
te: You can pay $0.685 for APEs, and then vote to turn them into common sha=
res worth $5.30.
Meanwhile presumably some number of common shareholders will=C2=A0dislike=
=C2=A0this, because closing the discount probably means lowering the value =
of the common shares, so they might vote against it. But (1) there are more=
 APEs than common shares, and (2) the APEs are much more motivated to vote =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0and much less likely to be held by retail =E2=80=94=C2=A0tha=
n the common. So AMC should be able to get shareholder approval to collapse=
 the two classes of stock.
Also AMC can just sell more APEs directly to hedge funds who promise to vot=
e to collapse the structure, helping the vote along.  Anyway:

AMC Entertainment Holdings,=C2=A0Inc. (NYSE: AMC and APE) (=E2=80=9CAMC=E2=
=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cthe Company=E2=80=9D), today announced it will raise $11=
0 million of new equity capital through the sale of APE units to Antara Cap=
ital, LP (=E2=80=9CAntara=E2=80=9D) in two tranches at a weighted average p=
rice of $0.660 per share.=C2=A0The APE unit closing price on the New York S=
tock Exchange on December=C2=A021, 2022 was $0.685.
Under the terms of the agreement, Antara, a current AMC debt holder, will a=
lso exchange $100 million principal amount of 2nd Lien Notes due 2026 for a=
pproximately 91.0 million APE units thereby reducing AMC=E2=80=99s outstand=
ing debt by $100 million. As a result of the $100 million principal debt re=
duction, future annual interest expense will be reduced by approximately $1=
0 million. ...
In addition, AMC=E2=80=99s Board of Directors is seeking to hold a special =
meeting for holders of both AMC common shares and APE units (voting togethe=
r) to vote on the following proposals:
=09To increase the authorized number of AMC common shares to permit the con=
version of APE units into AMC common shares.

=09To affect a reverse-split of AMC common shares at a 1:10 ratio.

=09To adjust authorized ordinary share capital such that, after giving effe=
ct to the above proposals if adopted, AMC would have the same ability to is=
sue additional common equity as it currently has to issue additional APE un=
its.

As part of the agreement, Antara has agreed to hold their APE units for up =
to 90 days and vote them at the special meeting in favor of the proposals.

I don=E2=80=99t know! It=E2=80=99s a very elegant trade. I suppose if you w=
anted to quibble, you could argue that AMC=E2=80=99s shareholders=C2=A0didn=
=E2=80=99t want=C2=A0it to issue more shares, so it found sort of a clever =
back-door way to rig the vote to allow it to issue more shares. If you are =
a shareholder who plans to vote no, you might be annoyed. But I tend to thi=
nk that selling tons of shares into a meme-stock market was the best possib=
le move for AMC, and its great corporate finance innovation. AMC=E2=80=99s =
management may not be giving shareholders exactly what they want, but it=E2=
=80=99s giving them what they=C2=A0should=C2=A0want, and that really is man=
agement=E2=80=99s job.

