<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong><em> This is=
 the last Money Stuff of 2022. We=E2=80=99ll be back the first week of Janu=
ary. Happy holidays!</em></p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">FTX</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course there will be several FTX movies, an=
d maybe the most cinematic scene in the whole story is the meeting that Car=
oline Ellison, the chief executive officer of Alameda Research, FTX=E2=80=
=99s affiliated trading firm, held to tell her employees that they=E2=80=99=
d been stealing FTX customer money. Imagine! Imagine coming into the compan=
y all-hands meeting at the lucrative trading firm you work at, in the Baham=
as, far away from your friends and family and competitors, in a slightly cu=
lt-like environment where your <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/30059877.263533/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvN2NmYmI4OT=
QtYTMzMi00NjI5LWE0MTctNGJjZGEyN2ViNmU3/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB40771ec0" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;"> every need is catered to</a> out of the firm=E2=80=99s enormous pro=
fits. And then your 28-year-old boss is like =E2=80=9Cso guys, a little bad=
 news, actually we=E2=80=99re a Ponzi? Sorry if I didn=E2=80=99t mention th=
at earlier.=E2=80=9D Everyone quit immediately, but much too late.=C2=A0</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That meeting happened on Nov. 9, the day after=
 FTX death-spiraled and tried to sell itself to Binance, and has been repor=
ted before. But now Ellison is cooperating with prosecutors and regulators,=
 so we have their version of her version of the meeting and, oof. Here is h=
ow the US Commodity Futures Trading Commission <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30059877.263533/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby=
9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3I0Nzh0Q3VqMV9PVS92MA/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cB7d74cc4c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">describes it</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the morning of November 9 at ap=
proximately 10 AM ET, after the announcement of the then-contemplated Binan=
ce acquisition, Ellison held an =E2=80=9Call-hands=E2=80=9D meeting with Al=
ameda staff. In that meeting, Ellison acknowledged that earlier that year, =
she, Bankman-Fried and other individuals had decided to use FTX customer as=
sets to pay Alameda=E2=80=99s debts, and that Wang and another FTX executiv=
e were aware of this. Specifically, in that meeting, Ellison stated that, =
=E2=80=9Cstarting last year=E2=80=9D Alameda was =E2=80=9Cborrowing a bunch=
 of money by open term loans=E2=80=9D and used those assets to =E2=80=9Cmak=
e very illiquid investments.=E2=80=9D Ellison further explained that follow=
ing the widespread decline of digital asset prices most of Alameda=E2=80=99=
s loans had been recalled and, in order to meet those recalls, Alameda borr=
owed =E2=80=9Ca bunch of funds=E2=80=9D from FTX, which in turn =E2=80=9Cle=
d to FTX having a shortfall in user funds.=E2=80=9D Ellison informed Alamed=
a staff that FTX had =E2=80=9Calways allowed=E2=80=9D Alameda to borrow cus=
tomer assets, and did not require collateral for those loans. She=C2=A0also=
 explained that Alameda could access user assets without requiring FTX=E2=
=80=99s approval as the =E2=80=9Cstructure=E2=80=9D allowed Alameda to =E2=
=80=9Cgo negative in coins.=E2=80=9D In response to an employee question, E=
llison also acknowledged that her November 6 tweet to the Binance CEO offer=
ing to buy his FTT holdings at $22 per token was =E2=80=9Ckind of a mislead=
ing thing to tweet=E2=80=9D and expressed remorse. Shortly after this meeti=
ng, most of Alameda=E2=80=99s staff resigned.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CGo negative in coins=E2=80=9D is an i=
ncredible euphemism, really. The idea is that Alameda could deposit, say, 1=
,000 Bitcoin at FTX, and then it would have a balance of 1,000 Bitcoin. And=
 then it could withdraw, say, 3,000 Bitcoin from FTX, and then it would hav=
e a balance of -2,000 Bitcoin. If you have a negative balance at your bank,=
 bad things happen. When Alameda had a negative balance at FTX, that was ju=
st fine. Until it wasn=E2=80=99t.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ellison and Gary Wang, the former chief techno=
logy officer of FTX, have agreed to plead guilty to federal fraud charges f=
or their role in the FTX implosion. (The plea agreements say that <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30059877.263533/aHR0cHM6L=
y9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3I0Nzh0Q3VqMV9P=
VS92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC7d74cc4c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Ellison</a> and <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30059877.263533/aHR0cHM6L=
y9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JXS2FpejYwa1NW=
ay92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe7f75556" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Wang</a>=C2=A0face maxi=
mum sentences of 110 and 50 years in prison, respectively, though presumabl=
y they will end up with=C2=A0substantial discounts for cooperating.) Last n=
ight, Sam Bankman-Fried, the founder of FTX and Alameda, <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30059877.263533/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxv=
b21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTItMjIvYmFua21hbi1mcmllZC1hcnJpdmV=
zLWluLW55LWNvdXJ0LWZvci1mdHgtZnJhdWQtYXJyYWlnbm1lbnQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTIyMjIyX0=
1PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlc=
m09MjIxMjIyJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB32529a=
21" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> landed in New York</a> to face similar charges. There is some=
thing of a prisoner=E2=80=99s-dilemma situation here, in that there was=C2=
=A0<em>in theory=C2=A0</em>the possibility that=C2=A0everyone at FTX=C2=A0a=
nd Alameda could have stuck together and said=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cwhat, we never =
did anything wrong,=E2=80=9D and that they might have=C2=A0persuaded a jury=
 of that. The odds were always low, but it is the approach that Bankman-Fri=
ed has taken in public interviews. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30059877.263533/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb2=
1iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2ZlYXR1cmVzLzIwMjItMTItMDIvaW5zaWRlLXNhbS1iYW5rbWFuLWZya=
WVkLXMtYmFoYW1pYW4tcGVudGhvdXNlLWFmdGVyLWZ0eC1zLWNvbGxhcHNlP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEy=
MjIyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV=
0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTIyMiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cB6c434476" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;"> Zeke Faux reported</a>=C2=A0earlier this month:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Part of FTX=E2=80=99s appeal was that it was m=
ostly a derivatives exchange, which allowed customers to trade =E2=80=9Con =
margin,=E2=80=9D meaning with borrowed money. That=E2=80=99s a key to his d=
efense. Bankman-Fried argues no one should be surprised that big traders on=
 FTX, including Alameda, were borrowing from the exchange, and that his fun=
d=E2=80=99s position just somehow got out of hand. =E2=80=9CEveryone was bo=
rrowing and lending,=E2=80=9D he says. =E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=99s been its cal=
ling card.=E2=80=9D But FTX=E2=80=99s normal margin system, crypto traders =
tell me, would never have permitted anyone to accumulate a debt that looked=
 like Alameda=E2=80=99s. When I ask if Alameda had to follow the same margi=
n rules as other traders, he admits the fund did not. =E2=80=9CThere was mo=
re leeway,=E2=80=9D he says. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ellison said that she, Bankman-Fried and his t=
wo top lieutenants=E2=80=94Gary Wang and Nishad Singh=E2=80=94had discussed=
 the shortfall. Instead of admitting Alameda=E2=80=99s failure, they decide=
d to use FTX customer funds to cover it, according to the people. If that=
=E2=80=99s true, all four executives would=E2=80=99ve knowingly committed f=
raud. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CSo, it=E2=80=99s not how I remember w=
hat happened,=E2=80=9D Bankman-Fried says. But he surprises me by acknowled=
ging that there had been a meeting, post-Luna crash, where they debated wha=
t to do about Alameda=E2=80=99s debts. The way he tells it, he was packing =
for a trip to DC and =E2=80=9Conly kibitzing on parts of the discussion.=E2=
=80=9D It didn=E2=80=99t seem like a crisis, he says. It was a matter of ex=
tending a bit more credit to a fund that already traded on margin and still=
 had a pile of collateral worth way more than enough to cover the loan.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is=C2=A0a story in which FTX was operatin=
g its legitimate business =E2=80=94=C2=A0extending margin leverage to trade=
rs on its exchange =E2=80=94=C2=A0and made some mistakes. The mistakes were=
 very bad =E2=80=94=C2=A0they involved giving billions of dollars to Alamed=
a, which it could not pay back, blowing up FTX and taking customer money wi=
th it =E2=80=94=C2=A0and also=C2=A0<em>very suspicious</em>, in that FTX ga=
ve this generous credit only to its own affiliated=C2=A0trading firm,=C2=A0=
secured largely by tokens that FTX had invented, and Alameda was lending a =
lot of that money to FTX/Alameda=E2=80=99s principals for their own persona=
l purposes. And, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3=
0059877.263533/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIw=
MjItMTItMDYveW91LWNhbi10LXRlbGwtYW5hbHlzdHMtdG9vLW11Y2g_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTIyMjI=
yX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3=
Rlcm09MjIxMjIyJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB45d=
58ebe" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;">  as I</a> have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/30059877.263533/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2=
FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTItMDEvc2JmLW1pc3NlZC1mdHgtcy1yaXNrcz9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMjIyM=
jJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1f=
dGVybT0yMjEyMjImdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBab=
acd3ed" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;">  argued</a>, even if this story was true, it is not much o=
f a defense to fraud charges, because FTX was going around telling everyone=
 that it had good automated risk systems that would prevent it from doing e=
xactly this sort of dumb thing, and lying about that <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30059877.263533/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21i=
ZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTItMTMvaG93LXRvLWRvLWZyYXVkLWF0LWE=
tZnV0dXJlcy1leGNoYW5nZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMjIyMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPW=
VtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjEyMjImdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduP=
W1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB65037089" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  is itself fraud=
</a>. Again, I don=E2=80=99t think this would have worked. But I suppose if=
 you got a bunch of smart earnest 20-somethings up on the witness stand and=
 they all said =E2=80=9Cyes we were extending credit to a margin customer, =
ordinary-course stuff, but then the market blew up and the loans defaulted,=
=E2=80=9D there was a=C2=A0<em>chance</em>.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But now Ellison and Wang will get up on the wi=
tness stand and, I assume, say something like =E2=80=9Coh obviously we knew=
 that was fraud, we were just doing it to steal customer money, we talked a=
bout that all the time.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s hard to see how Bankman-Fried=
 could rebut that. Just on paper the facts are very bad, but when you add t=
he testimony of his friends they become impossible.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other new news from Ellison and Wang=E2=80=
=99s cooperation is about the alleged manipulation of FTT tokens.<a class=
=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !=
important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3005=
9877.263533/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2NvbXBsYWludHMvMjAyMi9=
jb21wLXByMjAyMi0yMzQucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7fdc33bc" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">US Sec=
urities and Exchange Commission explains</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Beyond its =E2=80=9Cline of credit=
=E2=80=9D with FTX, Ellison, at Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s direction, caused A=
lameda to borrow billions of dollars from third party lenders. Those loans =
were backed in significant part by Alameda=E2=80=99s holdings of FTT=E2=80=
=94an illiquid crypto asset security that was issued by FTX and provided to=
 Alameda at no cost. Ellison, acting at the direction of Bankman-Fried, eng=
aged in automated purchases of FTT tokens on various platforms in order to =
increase the price of those tokens and inflate the value of Alameda=E2=80=
=99s collateral, which allowed Alameda to borrow even more money from exter=
nal lenders at increased risk to the lenders and to FTX=E2=80=99s investors=
 and customers, all in furtherance of the scheme.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In July 2019, when FTX launched FTT, Alameda r=
eceived a substantial portion of the 350 million FTT tokens that were minte=
d, including all of the =E2=80=9Ccompany tokens=E2=80=9D that were allocate=
d to FTX. Alameda did not pay for these tokens.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Alameda programmed its automated trading tools=
 (or =E2=80=9Cbots=E2=80=9D) to conduct trades and execute transactions to =
purchase FTT at specific prices. On more than one occasion, Alameda and Ell=
ison, at Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s direction, actively engaged in the trading=
 of FTT with the goal of supporting the price of the token. On these occasi=
ons, Alameda adjusted the trading parameters of its trading bots in order t=
o support the price of FTT.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For example, in 2019, there was downward press=
ure on the price of FTT as the token was being unlocked for early-stage inv=
estors. Bankman-Fried became concerned about, among other things, the psych=
ological effect of the price of FTT dropping below a specific threshold, an=
d instructed Ellison to have Alameda purchase FTT to support the price and =
avoid that outcome. In another instance in 2021, the price of FTT was again=
 facing downward pressure from external events, this time related to substa=
ntial sales of FTT by a third party. Bankman-Fried again instructed Ellison=
 to have Alameda purchase FTT on trading platforms to support the price.</p=
>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here again you <em>might</em> be able to get a=
round the objective facts, which are basically that Alameda, a crypto marke=
t maker, was buying FTT tokens when other people were selling. But if the C=
EO of Alameda gets on the stand and says =E2=80=9Cyes Sam Bankman-Fried tol=
d me to buy FTT tokens to manipulate the price up so that we could continue=
 to borrow billions of dollars against the inflated token we invented,=E2=
=80=9D that is harder to explain away.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The question I always have in situations like =
this is: How did they=C2=A0<em>think=C2=A0</em>this would go? What was the=
=C2=A0<em>good=C2=A0</em>outcome here? Why <em>do=C2=A0</em>all this?=C2=A0=
Many financial crimes have essentially the shape of Ponzi schemes, which by=
 their nature snowball: You take some money from new customers to pay fake =
returns to old customers, which requires you to take even more money from n=
ewer customers to keep paying the fake returns, etc., until the hole gets t=
oo big and you go to prison. If you start by stealing $1,000, pretty soon y=
ou need to steal $10,000, and then $100,000, and then you find yourself run=
ning a billion-dollar Ponzi. And there=E2=80=99s rarely a way to come back =
from that. It is hard to make back a billion dollars at the roulette tables=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You can keep this=C2=A0<em>going=C2=A0</em>for=
 a while, if you are good and lucky; Bernie Madoff ran a huge Ponzi for yea=
rs. But that doesn=E2=80=99t really=C2=A0<em>help</em>. The longer you run =
the Ponzi, the deeper the hole gets; being respectable and trusted for deca=
des doesn=E2=80=99t really get you the billions of dollars you need to plug=
 the hole. It is hard to grow your way out of it; growth mostly makes the p=
roblem worse.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there is something different about running=
 a crypto exchange, taking out margin loans against tokens that you made up=
 to invest in crypto venture capital projects. The asset that you are borro=
wing against is essentially=C2=A0<em>confidence in you: </em>in your exchan=
ge, in crypto generally, in your role as a leading figure in crypto. If tha=
t collapses, then your finances collapse and you find yourself in a Bahamia=
n jail cell. But what if it doesn't? If you go on long enough, then those F=
TT tokens that you made up =E2=80=94=C2=A0that entitle customers to discoun=
ts on FTX trading fees and a share of FTX revenue =E2=80=94=C2=A0become mor=
e and more valuable, and your decision to lend money against them looks fin=
e. (Your decision to=C2=A0<em>manipulate</em> them looks fine, too, because=
 in hindsight you can say =E2=80=9Cof course we bought when people were sel=
ling, we thought they were a bargain, and we were right.=E2=80=9D) Ultimate=
ly maybe those tokens become so valuable that they dwarf the customer money=
 that you, uh, misplaced, and you can easily plug the hole with the=C2=A0to=
kens.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Earlier this year, we <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30059877.263533/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZX=
JnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDUtMTAvYW5vdGhlci1hbGdvcml0aG1pYy1zd=
