" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  I wrote</a>,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cis (1) P=
onzi, (2) acceptance, (3) diversification, (4) permanence.=E2=80=9D This di=
d not work, because before Terra could complete its diversification it lost=
 market confidence, and everything went to zero.=C2=A0But I don=E2=80=99t t=
hink it was a terrible plan. If Terra <em>had=C2=A0</em>managed to be widel=
y accepted for long enough, it could have=C2=A0<em>printed its own money</e=
m>, and then=C2=A0<em>exchanged that for real money</em>, and then everythi=
ng would have been great. So close!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">FTX, too, printed its own money, and treated i=
t as money. At the end, as FTX was spiraling into bankruptcy, as the Binanc=
e bailout was falling apart, as Caroline Ellison was telling employees abou=
t the missing customer money, Sam Bankman-Fried was <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30059877.263533/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZ=
XJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMTQvZnR4LXMtYmFsYW5jZS1zaGVldC13=
