<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Honestly the APE thing is pretty clever. AMC E=
ntertainment Holdings Inc. has one incredible advantage=C2=A0and one bizarr=
e constraint. The advantage is that AMC is really really good at raising eq=
uity: It rode last year=E2=80=99s meme-stock wave <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30059877.263533/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJ=
nLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMDIvYW1jLWJyaW5ncy1vdXQtdGhlLXBvcG=
Nvcm4_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTIyMjIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291c=
mNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIxMjIyJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB67100cee" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  more expertly</a> than anyone els=
e, using retail investors=E2=80=99 enthusiasm for its stock=C2=A0to sell lo=
ts of stock at attractive prices to pay down debt.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The constraint is that, like most public compa=
nies, AMC has a corporate charter that=C2=A0limits the number of shares it =
can issue, and it is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/30059877.263533/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVz=
LzIwMjEtMDYtMDMvYW1jLWhhcy1hLWJpdC1tb3JlLXN0b2NrLXRvLXNlbGw_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTI=
yMjIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdX=
RtX3Rlcm09MjIxMjIyJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B743427bf" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;">  basically all out of shares</a>. To get more shares, i=
t needs to get a majority of its shareholders to approve an amendment to th=
e corporate charter authorizing more shares, and this is hard, for two reas=
ons:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Some shareholders seem to dislike the=
 idea of being =E2=80=9Cdiluted=E2=80=9D if AMC issues more shares. This st=
rikes me as misguided =E2=80=94=C2=A0if a company sells stock at a price th=
at is too high, that=E2=80=99s accretive! =E2=80=94=C2=A0but people worry.<=
/li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">More important, AMC has tons of re=
tail shareholders, and=C2=A0retail shareholders, stereotypically, <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30059877.263533/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDgtMjQvYW1jLXMtYXBl=
cy1taWdodC1zdGljay1hcm91bmQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTIyMjIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl=
1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIxMjIyJnV0bV9jYW1wYW=
lnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3e821bfa" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  don=E2=80=
=99t vote</a>. It needs a majority of all shares to vote in favor of the ch=
arter amendment, and it=E2=80=99s hard to do that if many of your sharehold=
ers don=E2=80=99t vote at all.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so AMC <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/30059877.263533/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vc=
GluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDgtMjMvYW1jLWdvZXMtYXBlP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEyMjIyMl9N=
T05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJ=
tPTIyMTIyMiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9f7d7d=
b5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">  came up with a novel idea</a>. It couldn=E2=80=99t sell any =
more common shares, so it would sell APE shares, =E2=80=9CAMC Preferred Equ=
ity units,=E2=80=9D a weird new instrument designed to look like common sto=
ck.=C2=A0The APE shares=C2=A0are not common stock, so they are not covered =
by the cap in=C2=A0the certificate of incorporation, but they are=C2=A0<em>=
like=C2=A0</em>common stock in most important ways. They are listed on the =
stock exchange and they have the same economic rights (to dividends, etc.) =
as the common stock does. Also, crucially, they=C2=A0<em>vote=C2=A0</em>wit=
h the common stock: Anything that needs shareholder approval is submitted t=
o a combined vote of the common and APE shares; each share, common or APE, =
gets one vote.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">AMC did not start by selling APEs; it started =
by giving them away. It distributed APEs to its existing common shareholder=
s, one APE per common share; the result was basically like a stock split, w=
here if you previously had 100 shares now you had 200, except half of them =
were APEs. This created a market for the APEs =E2=80=94=C2=A0now people had=
 them, they were bought and sold=C2=A0on the stock exchange. And=C2=A0<em>t=
hen=C2=A0</em>AMC started <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/30059877.263533/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXR=
hLzE0MTE1NzkvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTIyMTAyODMzL3RtMjIyNjM1MC0xXzQyNGI1Lmh0bQ/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cB5bb9e9cb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> selling APEs</a> to raise money. It wa=
s out of common shares, but it still had APEs.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In theory there were three ways this could go:=
</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The APEs and common shares, being mor=
e or less identical, would trade at more or less the same price. It would b=
e like any other company with dual-class shares. AMC would keep issuing mor=
e APEs to raise financing, and would get about as much money for the APEs a=
s it would for its common stock. Nobody would worry about the small differe=
nces between APEs and common shares.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px=
;">The APEs would be worth=C2=A0<em>more=C2=A0</em>than the common stock, b=
ecause they are funny? The ticker is APE. They are preferred stock, which y=
ou might think makes them preferable to the common stock. In this case, AMC=
 would keep issuing APEs to raise financing, and would get more money for t=
he APEs than it would for common stock, and would have created some value o=
ut of nothing. Or, rather, would have created some value out of leaning int=
o the meme-stock thing, which is how it creates value generally.</li>=09<li=
 style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The APEs would be worth=C2=A0<em>less=C2=A0<=
/em>than the common stock, because common stock is a normal obvious standar=
d thing, while a weird preferred unit is weird. In this case, AMC would hav=
e no choice but to keep issuing APEs to raise financing =E2=80=94=C2=A0it c=
an=E2=80=99t sell more common shares! =E2=80=94=C2=A0but would get less for=
 those APEs than it would for its common stock. The APE financings would be=
 dilutive: AMC would sell APEs for less than the price of common stock, but=
 the APEs would have the same economic rights as common stock. This would b=
e bad.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Option 3 was the most likely, and it is in fac=
t what happened. When APEs started trading in August, they were worth about=
 $6 or $7 per share, while the common stock was around $9 or $10. Yesterday=
 the common stock closed at $5.30; the APEs closed at $0.685, an 87% discou=
nt. That=E2=80=99s bad. If your common stock is worth $5.30, selling basica=
lly-common-stock for $0.685 is a bad corporate finance move.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But this problem comes with its own solution. =
AMC can still go back to shareholders anytime and ask them to vote to colla=
pse this back into a normal single-share structure, by authorizing=C2=A0mor=
e common shares and converting the APE shares into common shares. If a majo=
rity of shareholders approve, then each APE will turn into a common share, =
closing the discount. Maybe the common shares will maintain their value and=
 the APEs will go up to $5.30, or maybe they=E2=80=99ll both end up worth, =
say, $3, but in any case they=E2=80=99ll all be the same thing and trade at=
 the same price.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And, when AMC puts that proposition to a vote,=
 the common shareholders and the APE holders will all vote together. There =
will be=C2=A0<em>more=C2=A0</em>APE shares than common shares: Originally t=
he APEs were distributed to common shareholders 1 for 1, creating an equal =
number of APEs and common shares, and since then AMC has sold more APEs whi=
le the common share supply is capped. So the majority of voting shares belo=
ng to the APEs, which trade at a discount to the common. The APEs have ever=
y reason to vote to collapse their APEs back into common stock to close the=
 discount. The bigger the discount is, the more incentive they have to vote=
. And, the bigger the discount is, the more likely it is that some <em>prof=
essional=C2=A0</em>investor =E2=80=94=C2=A0a hedge fund, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0will buy up the APEs=C2=A0<em>in order to=C2=A0</em>vote: You can pay $0=
.685 for APEs, and then vote to turn them into common shares worth $5.30.</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile presumably some number of common sha=
reholders will=C2=A0<em>dislike=C2=A0</em>this, because closing the discoun=
t probably means lowering the value of the common shares, so they might vot=
e against it. But (1) there are more APEs than common shares, and (2) the A=
PEs are much more motivated to vote =E2=80=94=C2=A0and much less likely to =
be held by retail =E2=80=94=C2=A0than the common. So AMC should be able to =
get shareholder approval to collapse the two classes of stock.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also AMC can just sell more APEs directly to h=
edge funds who promise to vote to collapse the structure, helping the vote =
along. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30059877.26=
3533/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MTE1NzkvMDAwMT=
EwNDY1OTIyMTI5MzUzL3RtMjIzMzMxOGQxX2V4OTktMS5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
1de6350c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;"> Anyway</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">AMC Entertainment Holdings,=C2=A0Inc. (NYSE: A=
MC and APE) (=E2=80=9CAMC=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cthe Company=E2=80=9D), today=
 announced it will raise $110 million of new equity capital through the sal=
e of APE units to Antara Capital, LP (=E2=80=9CAntara=E2=80=9D) in two tran=
ches at a weighted average price of $0.660 per share.<span>=C2=A0</span>The=
 APE unit closing price on the New York Stock Exchange on December=C2=A021,=
 2022 was $0.685.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Under the terms of the agreement, Antara, a cu=
rrent AMC debt holder, will also exchange $100 million principal amount of =
2nd Lien Notes due 2026 for approximately 91.0 million APE units thereby re=
ducing AMC=E2=80=99s outstanding debt by $100 million. As a result of the $=
100 million principal debt reduction, future annual interest expense will b=
e reduced by approximately $10 million. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In addition, AMC=E2=80=99s Board of Directors =
is seeking to hold a special meeting for holders of both AMC common shares =
and APE units (voting together) to vote on the following proposals:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">To increase the authorized number of A=
MC common shares to permit the conversion of APE units into AMC common shar=
es.</li>
</ul>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">To affect a reverse-split of AMC commo=
n shares at a 1:10 ratio.</li>
</ul>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">To adjust authorized ordinary share ca=
pital such that, after giving effect to the above proposals if adopted, AMC=
 would have the same ability to issue additional common equity as it curren=
tly has to issue additional APE units.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As part of the agreement, Antara has agreed to=
 hold their APE units for up to 90 days and vote them at the special meetin=
g in favor of the proposals.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know! It=E2=80=99s a very eleg=
ant trade. I suppose if you wanted to quibble, you could argue that AMC=E2=
=80=99s shareholders=C2=A0<em>didn=E2=80=99t want=C2=A0</em>it to issue mor=
e shares, so it found sort of a clever back-door way to rig the vote to all=
ow it to issue more shares. If you are a shareholder who plans to vote no, =
you might be annoyed. But I tend to think that selling tons of shares into =
a meme-stock market was the best possible move for AMC, and its great corpo=
rate finance innovation. AMC=E2=80=99s management may not be giving shareho=
lders exactly what they want, but it=E2=80=99s giving them what they=C2=A0<=
em>should=C2=A0</em>want, and that really is management=E2=80=99s job.</p>
